Sure, here's an example of HTML and CSS code to create a sidebar with navlinks for "Home", "About", and "Contact":

HTML:

```
<div class="sidebar">
  <nav>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
      <li><a href="#">About</a></li>
      <li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
    </ul>
  </nav>
</div>
```

CSS:

```
.sidebar {
  position: fixed;
  left: 0;
  top: 0;
  width: 200px;
  height: 100%;
  background-color: #f2f2f2;
  padding: 20px;
}

.sidebar nav ul {
  list-style: none;
  padding: 0;
  margin: 0;
}

.sidebar nav ul li {
  margin-bottom: 10px;
}

.sidebar nav ul li a {
  color: #000;
  text-decoration: none;
  font-size: 18px;
}

.sidebar nav ul li a:hover {
  color: #007bff;
}
```

Feel free to modify the styles to fit your website's design.
